				<div class="post-top"><div class="date">10/15/10</div>
					<h1><a href="http://borgidacpas.com/2010/10/the-difference-between-capital-gains-and-ordinary-income/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to The Difference Between Capital Gains and Ordinary Income">The Difference Between Capital Gains and Ordinary Income</a></h1>
					<!--<div class="author">Author: <a href="http://borgidacpas.com/author/karen-tedford/" title="Posts by Karen Tedford">Karen Tedford</a></div>-->
					
				</div>
				<div class="entry">
					<p>Most long-term capital gains are taxed at 15% for 2010.&nbsp; This rate is scheduled to increase to 20% in 2011.&nbsp; Unfortunately, we need to say &ldquo;most&rdquo; because there are some exceptions as follows:</p>
<ul>
<li>Taxpayers in the 10% and 15% ordinary bracketâ€•0%</li>
<li>Certain depreciation recapture on real estate&mdash;25%</li>
<li>Collectibles&mdash;28% <a href="http://borgidacpas.com/2010/10/the-difference-between-capital-gains-and-ordinary-income/#more-1385" class="more-link">more&#8230;</a></li>
</ul>
